<p>The <b>Gaelic Athletic Association</b> (<b>GAA</b>; <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_language" title=3D"Irish language">Irish</a>: <i=
 lang=3D"ga">Cumann L=C3=BAthchleas Gael</i> <span class=3D"IPA nowrap" lan=
g=3D"ga-Latn-fonipa"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/Iris=
h" title=3D"Help:IPA/Irish">[=CB=88k=CA=8Am=CB=A0=C9=99n=CC=AA=CB=A0<span c=
lass=3D"wrap"> </span>=CB=88l=CC=AA=CB=A0u=CB=90=CB=8C=C3=A7l=CA=B2as=CB=A0=
<span class=3D"wrap"> </span>=CB=88=C9=A1e=CB=90l=CB=A0]</a></span>; <b>CLG=
</b>) is an Irish international <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Am=
ateur_sports" title=3D"Amateur sports">amateur sporting</a> and cultural or=
ganisation, focused primarily on promoting indigenous <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_games" title=3D"Gaelic games">Gaelic games</a> a=
nd pastimes,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-2"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
which include the traditional Irish sports of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Hurling" title=3D"Hurling">hurling</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Camogie" title=3D"Camogie">camogie</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_football" title=3D"Gaelic football">Gaelic f=
ootball</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_handball" titl=
e=3D"Gaelic handball">Gaelic handball</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/GAA_rounders" title=3D"GAA rounders">GAA rounders</a>. The ass=
ociation also promotes <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_music=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Irish music">Irish music</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_dance" title=3D"Irish dance">dance<=
/a>, as well as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_language=
" title=3D"Irish language">Irish language</a> and it also promotes environm=
ental stewardship through its Green Clubs initiative.
</p><p>As of 2014, the organisation had over 500,000 members,<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-membership_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-membership-1"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and =
declared total revenues of =E2=82=AC96.1 million in 2022.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_At=
hletic_Association#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Competitions Control Committ=
ee (CCC) of the Gaelic Athletic Association (GAA) governing bodies organise=
 the fixture list of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_games"=
 title=3D"Gaelic games">Gaelic games</a> within a <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/GAA_county" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"GAA county">GAA =
county</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provincial_councils"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Provincial councils">provincial councils</a=
>.
</p><p>Gaelic football and hurling are the most popular activities promoted=
 by the organisation, and the most popular sports in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Republic_of_Ireland" title=3D"Republic of Ireland">R=
epublic of Ireland</a> in terms of attendance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_Socia=
l_Significance_of_Sport_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-The_Social_Significanc=
e_of_Sport-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> Gaelic football is also the second most popular pa=
rticipation sport in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northern_Irel=
and" title=3D"Northern Ireland">Northern Ireland</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athlet=
ic_Association#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The women's version of these games, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ladies%27_Gaelic_football" title=
=3D"Ladies' Gaelic football">ladies' Gaelic football</a> and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camogie" title=3D"Camogie">camogie</a>, are orga=
nised by the independent but closely linked <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Ladies%27_Gaelic_Football_Association" title=3D"Ladies' Gaelic Fo=
otball Association">Ladies' Gaelic Football Association</a> and the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camogie_Association_of_Ireland" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Camogie Association of Ireland">Camogie Association o=
f Ireland</a>, respectively. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GAA_H=
andball" title=3D"GAA Handball">GAA Handball</a>, is the governing body for=
 the sport of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_handball" tit=
le=3D"Gaelic handball">handball</a>, while the other Gaelic sport, rounders=
, is managed by the GAA Rounders National Council (<a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Irish_language" title=3D"Irish language">Irish</a>: <i lan=
g=3D"ga">Comhairle Cluiche Corr na h=C3=89ireann</i>).
</p><p>Since its foundation in 1884, the association has grown to become a =
major influence in Irish sporting and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Culture_of_Ireland" title=3D"Culture of Ireland">cultural life</a>, wit=
h considerable reach into communities throughout Ireland and among the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_diaspora" title=3D"Irish diaspor=
a">Irish diaspora</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ESRI_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note=
-ESRI-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Foundation_and_history">Fou=
ndation and history</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DGaelic_Athletic_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Foundation and history"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Gaelic_Athletic_A=
ssociation" title=3D"History of the Gaelic Athletic Association">History of=
 the Gaelic Athletic Association</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Thurles_Liberty_Square_Hayes_Hotel_2012_09_06=
.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Thurles_Liberty_Square_Hayes_Hotel_2012_09_0=
6.jpg/250px-Thurles_Liberty_Square_Hayes_Hotel_2012_09_06.jpg" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"250" height=3D"194" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wid=
th=3D"2735" data-file-height=3D"2127"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hayes%27_Hotel" title=3D"Hayes' Hotel">Hayes' Hotel</a>=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thurles" title=3D"Thurles">Thu=
rles</a>, foundation site of the organisation</figcaption></figure>
<p>On 1 November 1884, a group of Irishmen gathered in the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hayes%27_Hotel" title=3D"Hayes' Hotel">Hayes' Hote=
l</a> billiard room to formulate a plan and establish an organisation to fo=
ster and preserve Ireland's unique games and athletic pastimes. Arising out=
 of the meeting, the Gaelic Athletic Association (GAA) was founded. The arc=
hitects and founding members were <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Michael_Cusack_(Gaelic_Athletic_Association)" title=3D"Michael Cusack (Gael=
ic Athletic Association)">Michael Cusack</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/County_Clare" title=3D"County Clare">County Clare</a>, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurice_Davin" title=3D"Maurice Davin">M=
aurice Davin</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_K._Bracke=
n" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Joseph K. Bracken">Joseph K. Bracken</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_St_George_McCarthy" title=
=3D"Thomas St George McCarthy">Thomas St George McCarthy</a>, a District In=
spector in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Irish_Constab=
ulary" title=3D"Royal Irish Constabulary">Royal Irish Constabulary</a>, P. =
J. Ryan of Tipperary, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Wyse_Po=
wer" title=3D"John Wyse Power">John Wyse Power</a> and John McKay.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Maurice Davin was ele=
cted president, Cusack, Wyse-Power and McKay were elected Secretaries and i=
t was agreed that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Croke" ti=
tle=3D"Thomas Croke">Archbishop Croke</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Charles_Stewart_Parnell" title=3D"Charles Stewart Parnell">Charles=
 Stewart Parnell</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_D=
avitt" title=3D"Michael Davitt">Michael Davitt</a> would be asked to become=
 Patrons.
</p><p>In 1922 it turned over the job of promoting <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Sport_of_athletics" title=3D"Sport of athletics">athletics=
</a> to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Athletic_and_=
Cycling_Association" title=3D"National Athletic and Cycling Association">Na=
tional Athletic and Cycling Association</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Associ=
ation#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Competitions">Competitions<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGaelic_Athle=
tic_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: C=
ompetitions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Gaelic_Athle=
tic_Association_competitions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"List of Gaelic=
 Athletic Association competitions">List of Gaelic Athletic Association com=
petitions</a></div>
<p>The GAA organises a number of competitions at divisional, county, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter_county" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Inter county">inter-county</a>, provincial, <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/GAA_Interprovincial_Championship" title=3D"GAA Interprovinci=
al Championship">inter-provincial</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/All-Ireland#In_sports" title=3D"All-Ireland">national (All-Ireland)=
</a> levels. A number of competitions follow a progressive format in which,=
 for example, the winners of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All=
-Ireland_Senior_Club_Football_Championship#Format" title=3D"All-Ireland Sen=
ior Club Football Championship">club county football competition</a> progre=
ss to a competition involving the top clubs from each county in the provinc=
e, with the champions from each province progressing through a series of na=
tional finals.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Cultural_activities">Cultur=
al activities</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DGaelic_Athletic_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"=
Edit section: Cultural activities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The association has had a long history of promoting Irish culture.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Through a division of the association known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Sc%C3%B3r" title=3D"Sc=C3=B3r">Sc=C3=B3r</a> (Irish for "score=
"), the association promotes Irish cultural activities, running competition=
s in music, singing, dancing and storytelling.
</p><p>Rule 4 of the GAA's official guide states:
</p>
<blockquote><p><i>The Association shall actively support the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_language" title=3D"Irish language">Irish l=
anguage</a>, traditional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_dan=
cing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Irish dancing">Irish dancing</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_music" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Irish music">music</a>, song, and other aspects of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_culture" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Irish =
culture">Irish culture</a>. It shall foster an awareness and love of the na=
tional ideals in the people of Ireland, and assist in promoting a community=
 spirit through its clubs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-1=
0"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup></i></p></blockquote>
<p>The group was formally founded in 1969 and is promoted through various A=
ssociation clubs throughout Ireland (as well as some clubs outside Ireland)=
.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Grounds">Grounds</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGaelic_Athletic_Associ=
ation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Grounds"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Gaelic_Athle=
tic_Association_stadiums" title=3D"List of Gaelic Athletic Association stad=
iums">List of Gaelic Athletic Association stadiums</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Clgghaothdobhair.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1=
e/Clgghaothdobhair.jpg/960px-Clgghaothdobhair.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"520" height=3D"107" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2045" =
data-file-height=3D"420"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/C.L.G._Ghaoth_Dobhair" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"C.L.G. Ghaoth =
Dobhair">=C3=81ras Mhic Eiteag=C3=A1in</a> clubhouse in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gweedore" title=3D"Gweedore">Gweedore</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/County_Donegal" title=3D"County Donegal">Cou=
nty Donegal</a>. These grounds resemble the typical clubhouses to be found =
in rural areas all over Ireland.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The association has many stadiums scattered throughout Ireland and beyon=
d. Every county and nearly all clubs have grounds, with varying capacities =
and utilities, where they play their home games.
</p><p>The hierarchical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Structure_=
of_the_GAA" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Structure of the GAA">structure =
of the GAA</a> is applied to the use of grounds. Clubs play at their own gr=
ounds for the early rounds of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
List_of_Gaelic_Athletic_Association_competitions#Club" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"List of Gaelic Athletic Association competitions">club champions=
hip</a>, while the latter rounds from quarter-finals to finals are usually =
held at a county ground, i.e. the ground where <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/GAA_county" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"GAA county">inter-c=
ounty</a> games take place or where the county board is based.
</p><p>The provincial championship finals are usually played at the same ve=
nue every year. However, there have been exceptions, such as in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_GAA" title=3D"Ulster GAA">Ulster</a>, =
where in 2004 and 2005 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_=
Senior_Football_Championship" title=3D"Ulster Senior Football Championship"=
>Ulster Football Finals</a> were played in Croke Park, as the anticipated a=
ttendance was likely to far exceed the capacity of the traditional venue of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Tiernach%27s_Park" title=3D"St=
 Tiernach's Park">St Tiernach's Park</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Clones,_County_Monaghan" title=3D"Clones, County Monaghan">Clones</=
a>.
</p>
