6,197</li></ul>
<p>Research by former <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermanagh_GA=
A" title=3D"Fermanagh GAA">Fermanagh</a> county footballer Niall Cunningham=
 led to the publication in 2016 by his website, gaapitchlocator.net, of a m=
ap of 1,748 GAA grounds in Ireland, ranging from 24 grounds in his own coun=
ty to 171 in Cork.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-12"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Nationalism_and_community_r=
elations">Nationalism and community relations</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGaelic_Athletic_Association&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Nationalism and community rela=
tions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>The association has, since its inception, been closely associated with <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_nationalism" title=3D"Irish n=
ationalism">Irish nationalism</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cit=
e_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-15"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> and this has continued to the present, particularly in relatio=
n to Northern Ireland,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sugden_&amp;_Harvie_16-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Ass=
ociation#cite_note-Sugden_&amp;_Harvie-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> where the sports are=
 played predominantly by members of the mainly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Irish_Catholic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Irish Catholic"=
>Catholic</a> nationalist community, and many in the Protestant unionist po=
pulation consider themselves excluded by a perceived political ethos.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-la84foundation.org_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-la84foundati=
on.org-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-18"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> According to one sports historian, the GAA "is arguably the mo=
st striking example of politics shaping sport in modern history".<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A perception within <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norther=
n_Ireland" title=3D"Northern Ireland">Northern Ireland</a> <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unionism_in_Ireland" title=3D"Unionism in Ireland"=
>unionist</a> circles that the GAA is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Irish_nationalism" title=3D"Irish nationalism">nationalist</a> organi=
sation<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is reinforced by =
the naming of some GAA grounds, clubs, competitions and trophies after prom=
inent nationalists or republicans.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cit=
e_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-23"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-24"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Other critics point to protectionist rules such as Rule 42 which pro=
hibits competing, chiefly British, sports (referred to by some as "garrison=
 games"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-crokeParkMassacre_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-=
crokeParkMassacre-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Paul_Ward_2004_p._79_2=
7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_At=
hletic_Association#cite_note-Paul_Ward_2004_p._79-27"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Tim_Pat_Coogan_2000_p.179_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-Tim_Pat_C=
oogan_2000_p.179-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/List_of_Gaelic_Games_terminology#F" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"List o=
f Gaelic Games terminology">
foreign sports</a>) from GAA grounds. As a result, the GAA became a target =
for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster_loyalism" title=3D"Ulst=
er loyalism">loyalist</a> paramilitaries during <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/The_Troubles" title=3D"The Troubles">the Troubles</a> when a =
number of GAA supporters were killed and clubhouses damaged.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaeli=
c_Athletic_Association#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_A=
ssociation#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As the profile of Gaelic football has =
been raised in Ulster so too has there been an increase in the number of se=
ctarian attacks on Gaelic clubs in Northern Ireland.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athlet=
ic_Association#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some of the protectionist rules are as follows:
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rule_42_and_other_sports_in=
_GAA_grounds">Rule 42 and other sports in GAA grounds</h3><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGaelic_Athletic_Association&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Rule 42 and other spor=
ts in GAA grounds"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule_42" title=3D"Rule 42">Rule=
 42</a> (Rule 5.1 in the 2009 rulebook)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Associatio=
n#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> prohibits the use of GAA property for games wit=
h interests in conflict with the interests of the GAA referred to by some a=
s "garrison games"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-crokeParkMassacre_26-1" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association=
#cite_note-crokeParkMassacre-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Paul_Ward_2=
004_p._79_27-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-Paul_Ward_2004_p._79-27"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Tim_Pat_Coogan_2000_p.179_28-1" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_not=
e-Tim_Pat_Coogan_2000_p.179-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/List_of_Gaelic_Games_terminology#F" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"List of Gaelic Games terminology">foreign sports</a>. Current rules st=
ate that GAA property may only be used for the purpose or in connection wit=
h the playing of games controlled by the association. Sports not considered=
 'in conflict' with the GAA <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_o=
f_non-Gaelic_games_played_in_Croke_Park" title=3D"List of non-Gaelic games =
played in Croke Park">have been permitted</a>.
</p><p>On 16 April 2005 the GAA's congress voted to temporarily relax Rule =
42 and allow international soccer and rugby to be played in the stadium whi=
le Lansdowne Road Football Ground was closed for redevelopment.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ga=
elic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The first soccer and ru=
gby union games permitted in Croke Park took place in early 2007, the first=
 such fixture being <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ireland_nation=
al_rugby_union_team" title=3D"Ireland national rugby union team">Ireland</a=
>'s home match in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Six_Nations_=
Championship" title=3D"Six Nations Championship">Six Nations Rugby Union Ch=
ampionship</a> against <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/France_nati=
onal_rugby_union_team" title=3D"France national rugby union team">France</a=
>.
</p><p>In addition to the opening of Croke Park to competing sports, local =
GAA units have sought to rent their facilities out to other sports organisa=
tions for financial reasons in violation of Rule 42.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-sta=
teOfTheGame_34-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-stateOfTheGame-34"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The continued =
existence of Rule 42 has proven to be controversial since the management of=
 Croke Park has been allowed to earn revenue by renting the facility out to=
 competing sports organisations, but local GAA units which own smaller faci=
lities cannot.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-stateOfTheGame_34-1" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_n=
ote-stateOfTheGame-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-colmORourkeRule42_3=
6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_At=
hletic_Association#cite_note-colmORourkeRule42-36"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is also s=
aid that it is questionable as to whether or not such rental deals would be=
 damaging to the GAA's interests.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-stateOfTheGame_34-2" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic=
_Association#cite_note-stateOfTheGame-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Defunct_rules">Defunct rule=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGaelic_Ath=
letic_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Defunct rules"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>The GAA has had some notable rules in the past which have since been abo=
lished. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule_21" title=3D"Rule 21"=
>Rule 21</a>, instituted in 1897 when it was suspected that <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Irish_Constabulary" title=3D"Royal Irish Co=
nstabulary">Royal Irish Constabulary</a> spies were trying to infiltrate th=
e organization, prohibited members of the British forces from membership of=
 the GAA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-37"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Th=
e rule was abolished after an overwhelming majority voted for its removal a=
t a special congress convened in November 2001.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_As=
sociation#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#c=
ite_note-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rule_27" =
title=3D"Rule 27">Rule 27</a>, sometimes referred to as <i>The Ban</i>, dat=
ed from 1901 and banned GAA members from taking part in or watching non Gae=
lic games. During that time people such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Douglas_Hyde" title=3D"Douglas Hyde">Douglas Hyde</a>, GAA patron =
and then President of Ireland, was expelled for attending a soccer internat=
ional.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Rule =
27 was abolished in 1971.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-41=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cross-community_outreach_in=
_Northern_Ireland">Cross-community outreach in Northern Ireland</h3><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGaelic_Athletic_Associa=
tion&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Cross-commu=
nity outreach in Northern Ireland"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The association points out the role of members of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Religion_in_Ireland" title=3D"Religion in Ireland">minor=
ity religions</a> in the membership throughout its history. For example, th=
e Protestant <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Boothman" title=
=3D"Jack Boothman">Jack Boothman</a> was <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/List_of_Presidents_of_the_Gaelic_Athletic_Association" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"List of Presidents of the Gaelic Athletic Association">pr=
esident</a> of the organisation from 1993 to 1997, while Sam Maguire was a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Church_of_Ireland" title=3D"Church=
 of Ireland">Church of Ireland</a> member. Nonetheless, to address concerns=
 of unionists, the association's Ulster Council has embarked on a number of=
 initiatives aimed at making the association and Gaelic games more accessib=
le to northern Protestants. In November 2008, the council launched a <i>Com=
munity Development Unit</i>, which is responsible for "Diversity and Commun=
ity Outreach initiatives".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-4=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> The C=C3=BAchulainn Initiative is a cross-community program =
aimed at establishing teams consisting of Catholic and Protestant schoolchi=
ldren with no prior playing experience.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ulsterAnnualRepo=
rt_43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaeli=
c_Athletic_Association#cite_note-ulsterAnnualReport-43"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Cross-c=
ommunity teams such as the Belfast Cuchulainn under-16 hurling team have be=
en established and gone on to compete at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Continental_Youth_Championship" title=3D"Continental Youth Champ=
ionship">Continental Youth Championship</a> in the USA.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
ulsterAnnualReport_43-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-ulsterAnnualReport-43"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Similar hurling and Gaelic football teams have since emerged in Ar=
magh, Fermanagh, Limavady.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-4=
4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>=20
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Hassan" title=3D"David Hassa=
n">David Hassan</a>, from the University of Ulster, has written about the c=
ross community work of the association and other sporting bodies in Ulster.=
<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:n=
owrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_nee=
ded" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs re=
ferences to reliable sources. (May 2020)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</=
sup>
</p><p>The 'Game of three-halves' cross-community coaching initiative was e=
stablished in predominantly Protestant east Belfast in 2006. Organised thro=
ugh Knock Presbyterian Church, this scheme brings Association coaches to wo=
rk alongside their soccer and rugby counterparts to involve primary school =
children at summer coaching camps.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cit=
e_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-councilPlans_46-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#=
cite_note-councilPlans-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Ulster Council is also establish=
ing cross-community football and hurling teams in schools and is developing=
 links with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulster-Scots_Agenc=
y" title=3D"Ulster-Scots Agency">Ulster-Scots Agency</a> and the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Church_of_Ireland" title=3D"Church of Irelan=
d">Church of Ireland</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-councilPlans_46-1" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Associati=
on#cite_note-councilPlans-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The council has also undertaken a=
 series of meetings with political parties and community groups who would h=
ave traditionally have had no involvement in the association.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-councilPlans_46-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-councilPlans-46"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_community_outreach">O=
ther community outreach</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DGaelic_Athletic_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11"=
 title=3D"Edit section: Other community outreach"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In January 2011, the then President of Ireland, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mary_McAleese" title=3D"Mary McAleese">Mary McAleese</a>, =
announced the launch of an island-wide project called the "GAA Social Initi=
ative". This aims to address the problem of isolation in rural areas where =
older people have limited engagement with the community.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_At=
hletic_Association#cite_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The initiative was later expan=
ded by teaming up with the Irish Farmers Association to integrate that orga=
nisation's volunteers into the initiative.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Associa=
tion#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Participation_outside_Irela=
nd">Participation outside Ireland</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DGaelic_Athletic_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sec=
tion=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Participation outside Ireland"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Clubs_outside_Ireland">Club=
s outside Ireland</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DGaelic_Athletic_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=
=3D"Edit section: Clubs outside Ireland"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Gaeli=
c_games_clubs_outside_Ireland" title=3D"List of Gaelic games clubs outside =
Ireland">List of Gaelic games clubs outside Ireland</a></div>
<p>Members of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_diaspora" =
title=3D"Irish diaspora">Irish diaspora</a> have set-up clubs in a number o=
f regions and countries outside of Ireland, and there are GAA clubs in the =
United States, Australia, Britain, Canada, China, continental Europe and el=
sewhere.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The GAA World Games were first played in Abu Dhabi in 2015.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The next edition w=
as played in Dublin in 2016 with subsequent editions to be played in Irelan=
d every three years. The 2019 games were awarded to <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Waterford" title=3D"Waterford">Waterford</a>,<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ga=
elic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but the next edition in=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derry" title=3D"Derry">Derry</a><=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> was deferred=
 to 2023 due to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/COVID-19_pande=
mic" title=3D"COVID-19 pandemic">COVID</a> pandemic.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Internationals">Internation=
als</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGaelic_A=
thletic_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Internationals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>While some units of the association outside Ireland participate in Irish=
 competitions, the association itself does not organise regular internation=
al games played according to the rules of either Gaelic football or hurling=
. However, the first international match between France and Italy was playe=
d in 2014.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-53"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Compromise rules have been reached with two "related sports".
</p><p>Hurlers play an annual fixture against a national <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shinty" title=3D"Shinty">shinty</a> team from <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scotland" title=3D"Scotland">Scotland</a=
>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Rules_Footbal=
l" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International Rules Football">Internation=
al Rules Football</a> matches have taken place between an <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ireland_international_rules_football_team" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ireland international rules football team">Irish nat=
ional team</a> drawn from the ranks of Gaelic footballers, against an <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia_international_rules_football_=
team" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Australia international rules football=
 team">Australian national team</a> drawn from the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Australian_Football_League" title=3D"Australian Football L=
eague">Australian Football League</a>. The venue alternates between Ireland=
 and Australia. In December 2006, the International series between Australi=
a and Ireland was called off due to excessive violence in the matches,<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but resumed in O=
ctober 2008 when Ireland won a two test series in Australia.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaeli=
c_Athletic_Association#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Irish welcomed the All=
 Australian team at the headquarters of the GAA (Croke Park) on 21 November=
 2015. It was single one-off test match, which led the Irish to reclaim the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cormac_McAnallen" title=3D"Cormac=
 McAnallen">Cormac McAnallen</a> Cup by a score of 56=E2=80=9352.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Handball">Handball</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DGaelic_Athletic_Asso=
ciation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Handball=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>The international dimension of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Gaelic_handball" title=3D"Gaelic handball">Gaelic handball</a> includes a W=
orld Championship tournament,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_not=
e-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-57" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-57"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> alongside a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_1-Wall_=
Tour" title=3D"European 1-Wall Tour">European Tour</a> and US Semi-Professi=
onal Tour.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-euro1wall_58-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-eur=
o1wall-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-59"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> The 4-Wall and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intern=
ational_fronton" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International fronton">1-Wa=
ll</a> codes of the game are played around the world [with slightly differe=
nt rules depending on which country one is playing in] and the World Handba=
ll Championships are organised by the World Handball Council.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gael=
ic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/European_1-Wall_Tour" title=3D"European 1-Wall Tour">Euro=
pean Tour</a> has been set up with players from across Europe participating=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-euro1wall_58-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-euro1wall-58">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> 4-Wall Handball is played primarily in Ireland, the US and Cana=
da while the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_fronton=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"International fronton">1-Wall</a> code is =
played (in addition to the three mentioned) in Belgium, France, Holland, It=
aly, Spain and the UK.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-euro1wall_58-2" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cit=
e_note-euro1wall-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Winter_training_ban">Winter=
 training ban</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DGaelic_Athletic_Association&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D=
"Edit section: Winter training ban"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>To address concerns about player <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Occupational_burnout" title=3D"Occupational burnout">burnout</a>, the ass=
ociation adopted a rule in 2007 that prohibited collective training for int=
er-county players for a period of two months every winter.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_=
Athletic_Association#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This has proven to be contro=
versial in that it is difficult to enforce; in the drive to stay competitiv=
e, managers have found ways to avoid it, such as organising informal 'athle=
tic clubs' and other activities that they can use to work on the physical f=
itness of players without overtly appearing to be training specifically at =
Gaelic games.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_Athletic_Association#cite_note-62"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
